## Conversation
Second commit for issue #5421 (see the anthropic commit's note for full context).
The issue title says "Anthropic (Bedrock)". The reporter's illustrative captured
output had `content` as a STRING, snake_case `stop_reason`, and a `latency_ms`
field — that shape is produced ONLY by bedrock_stream_accumulator (the Anthropic
accumulator never adds latency_ms), so the Bedrock converse_stream path is
squarely in scope alongside the Anthropic SDK path.

## Root cause
weave/integrations/bedrock/bedrock_sdk.py: bedrock_stream_accumulator built
acc["content"] as a flat string via `acc["content"] += value["contentBlockDelta"]
["delta"]["text"]`. Two bugs:
  1. A string can't represent a tool call, so tool_use was dropped.
  2. On a tool-use delta, delta == {"toolUse": {"input": "<partial json>"}} has no
     "text" key -> KeyError. op.py only catches StopIteration around the accumulator
     (see anthropic note), so this KeyError re-raises into the user's stream loop and
     breaks iteration. So this path was worse than Anthropic's silent drop.

## Fix (design confirmed via Codex consult)
Asked Codex (CLAUDE.md requires consult on data-shape/schema forks): keep content
as a string + add a tool_uses field (back-compat, hybrid Weave-only schema) vs
switch content to a list of Converse-shaped blocks. Codex recommended the list:
the accumulator should reconstruct the model's actual output message, and a list
unifies streaming with the non-streaming Converse `output.message.content`
(`[{"text":...},{"toolUse":{...}}]`). A Weave-only hybrid splits the message across
two fields and burdens every consumer.
Implemented:
  - acc["content"] is now a list[dict].
  - contentBlockStart with start.toolUse -> append {"toolUse": {toolUseId, name,
    "input": ""}} at contentBlockIndex.
  - contentBlockDelta text -> get/create {"text": ""} at index, append text.
  - contentBlockDelta toolUse -> append delta.toolUse.input (raw JSON str) to the
    block's input buffer.
  - contentBlockStop -> _finalize_converse_tool_input parses the JSON string into a
    dict (empty -> {}; unparseable -> kept verbatim, never dropped).
  - messageStart/messageStop/metadata (role, stop_reason, usage, latency_ms)
    unchanged.
Helpers: _converse_block_index (defensive int coercion), _get_or_create_converse_block
(append in contiguous index order, pad gaps with {} rather than raise),
_parse_converse_tool_input, _finalize_converse_tool_input. Indices in ConverseStream
are contiguous/ascending so list position == contentBlockIndex.

## BREAKING change + test update
This changes the traced output shape for converse_stream from `content: str` to
`content: list`. Only one consumer read it as a string: the existing
test_bedrock_converse_stream asserted `"To list all text files" in output["content"]`
(substring on a str). Updated it to scan text blocks
(`any("..." in block.get("text","") for block in content)`) — preserves the test's
intent (text is captured) while adapting the mechanism (tests-only-tighten rule).
Cost/usage summary (bedrock_on_finish_converse) reads output["usage"] only, so it is
unaffected by the content reshape. Grepped: no other consumer of the stream content
string (the other ["content"] hits are non-streaming converse/invoke/guardrail, which
already use list/dict shapes).

## Testing
Bedrock tests use moto + a mock _make_api_call returning a MockStream (no VCR).
Added MOCK_STREAM_TOOL_EVENTS (text block index 0 + tool_use get_weather index 1,
input streamed as two JSON fragments '{"location":' + ' "San Francisco, CA"}'),
mock_converse_stream_tool_make_api_call, and test_bedrock_converse_stream_tool_use.
The test asserts the stream consumes without raising (regression for the KeyError),
that content has both the text block and the toolUse block with input parsed to
{"location": "San Francisco, CA"}, stop_reason tool_use, and usage 410/60/470.
Verified the accumulator directly on synthesized streams: text-only ->
[{"text":...}] (no regression), text+tool, and empty-input tool -> input {}.
Ran anthropic+bedrock suites on sqlite: 26 passed. ruff/ty clean; pyright/mypy show
only the pre-existing anthropic_stream_accumulator errors (unrelated).

## Hints for future agents
